'''Annie Griffin''' (born in 1960, [[New York City]]) is an American writer and director.
Griffin relocated to the UK in 1981. She started out as an experimental theatre writer and director in the 1980s, with her first notable work being Blackbeard the Pirate in 1987, at the ICA in London.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.curtisbrown.co.uk/client/annie-griffin|title=Curtis Brown|website=www.curtisbrown.co.uk|access-date=2017-11-18}}</ref> In the early 1990s she worked creating animated [[Station identification|idents]] for [[MTV]]. In 1993 she worked as an actress on the [[Academy Award|Oscar]] nominated short animated film ''The Village''. Through the 90's she worked on a number of short works including the ''Seven Sins:Wrath'' which featured [[Paul Kaye]] and [[David Walliams]].
In 1999, Griffin wrote and directed ''[[Coming Soon (1999 TV film)|Coming Soon]]'',<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thisisliveart.co.uk/resources/catalogue/coming-soon-part-1|title=Coming Soon: Part 1 - Catalogue - Live Art Development Agency|author=|date=|website=Live Art Development Agency|accessdate=11 November 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bfi.org.uk/films-tv-people/4ce2b82fcbefc|title=Coming Soon[01/07/99] (1999)|author=|date=|website=bfi.org.uk|accessdate=11 November 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.theguardian.com/media/1999/jun/18/tvandradio.television3|title=A screen full of nothing|first=Adam|last=Sweeting|date=18 June 1999|website=the Guardian|accessdate=11 November 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/media/required-reading-9140224.html|title=Required reading|author=|date=|website=independent.co.uk|accessdate=11 November 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.imdb.com/title/tt0204083/|title=Coming Soon|author=|date=|publisher=|accessdate=11 November 2018|via=imdb.com}}</ref>
Griffin wrote and directed [[The Book Group]], a comedy drama which aired on Channel 4 in the United Kingdom between 2002 and 2003, and ran for two series. It was the winner of two [[BAFTA Scotland]] awards.
In 2005, Griffin wrote and directed ''[[Festival (2005 film)|Festival]]'' a black comedy set during the [[Edinburgh Festival Fringe]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.futuremovies.co.uk/filmmaking/lunatic-fringe/michelle-thomas|title=Lunatic Fringe|date=2005-12-07|work=Future Movies|access-date=2017-11-18|language=en-GB}}</ref>
In 2011, Griffin directed two episodes of Channel 4 [[Comedy-drama|comedy drama]] series ''[[Fresh Meat (TV series)|Fresh Meat]]''. When the series returned in 2012, she directed episodes five to eight, and also wrote episode six.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/name/nm0341112/|title=Annie Griffin|website=IMDb|access-date=2017-11-18}}</ref>
