{{Infobox ancient site |name = Handoga |alternate_name = |image = Handoga.JPG |image_size = 300px |alt = |caption = |map_type = Djibouti |relief = yes |map_alt = Map showing location of Handoga in Djibouti |coordinates = {{coord|11|05|27|N|42|14|56|E|display=inline,title}} |location = [[Dikhil Region]], [[Djibouti]] |region = |type = |part_of = |length = |width = |area = |height = {{convert|402|m}} |builder = |material = |built = c. 3000 BC |abandoned = |epochs = |cultures = |dependency_of = |occupants = |event = |excavations = 1970 |archaeologists = |condition = |ownership = |management = |public_access = |website = |notes = }} '''Handoga''' is located 14 km to the west of [[Dikhil]], [[Djibouti]]. During the first excavations in 1970, archaeologists discovered foundations of stone houses and the walls of a stone edifice with a recess that faces [[Mecca]].
==History== They have also updated shards of ceramics, chipped stone tools and a glass bead. The engravings oldest discovered to date are from the fourth or third millennium BC In the pre-Islamic period, the most famous is the site of Handoga there where the ruins of a village squares subcircular dry stone delivered different objects. An old settlement, Handoga is the site of numerous ancient ruins and buildings, many of obscure origins. Including ceramic shards matching vases used brazier, or containers that can hold water, several choppers and [[microlith]]s, blades, drills, trenchers basalt, rhyolite or obsidian. A team of archaeologists discover an [[elephant]] date of 1.6 million years near the area. Also a pearl orange coralline, three glass paste, etc.. No trace of metal object.
