{{Infobox book | name = Lost Moon: The Perilous Voyage of Apollo 13 | image = Lost Moon.jpg | image_size = | caption = Cover of the ''Lost Moon'' first Edition | alt = | author = [[Jim Lovell]] and [[Jeffrey Kluger]] | title_orig = | translator = | illustrator = | cover_artist = | country = United States | language = English | series = | subject = [[Aerospace engineering]] | genre = Non-Fiction | published = {{plainlist| * 1994 ([[Houghton Mifflin Company]]) * 1995 ([[Pocket Books]]) }} | media_type = Print | pages = 378 (first edition) | awards = | isbn = 0-395-67029-2 | oclc = | dewey = 629.45 | congress = | preceded_by = | preceded_by_quotation_marks = | followed_by = | followed_by_quotation_marks = | wikisource = }}
'''''Lost Moon: The Perilous Voyage of Apollo 13''''' (published in [[paperback]] as '''''Apollo 13'''''), is a non-fiction book first published in 1994 by astronaut [[Jim Lovell|James Lovell]] and journalist [[Jeffrey Kluger]], about the failed April 1970 [[Apollo 13]] lunar landing mission which Lovell commanded. The book is the basis of the 1995 film adaptation ''[[Apollo 13 (film)|Apollo 13]]'', directed by [[Ron Howard]].
==Background== Apollo 13 was the third mission of the [[Apollo program]] intended to land men on the Moon. An explosion of an onboard [[liquid oxygen]] tank in the Service Module, when the craft was close to reaching the Moon, crippled the electrical power generation and propulsion systems for the [[Apollo Command/Service Module|Command Module]] ''Odyssey''. This necessitated the abort of the lunar landing, and placed the lives of astronauts Lovell, [[Jack Swigert]], and [[Fred Haise]] in serious jeopardy. The mission became famous for the safe return of the men, made possible by the [[flight controller]]s' resourceful adaptation of the electrical, propulsion, and life support systems of the [[Apollo Lunar Module|LM (Lunar Module)]] ''Aquarius'' as a "lifeboat".
==Physical description== * Hardcover, 378 pages * Publisher: Houghton Mifflin (T) (October 1994) * Language: English * {{ISBN|0-395-67029-2}} * Dimensions: 1.5 × 6.2 × 9.2&nbsp;inches
