{{Multiple issues| {{refimprove|date=May 2015}} {{Technical|date=June 2015}} }}
{{Infobox book <!-- |italic title = (see above) --> | name = | image = File:The Sublime Object of Ideology cover image.jpg | caption = Cover of the first edition | author = [[Slavoj Žižek]] | title_orig = | translator = | illustrator = | cover_artist = | country = United Kingdom | language = English | series = | subject = [[Ideology]] | publisher = [[Verso Books]] | publisher2 = | pub_date = December 1989 | english_pub_date = | media_type = Print | pages = 336 | awards = | isbn = 978-0860919711 | oclc = 21158412 | dewey = | congress = | preceded_by = | followed_by = | wikisource = }} '''''The Sublime Object of Ideology''''' is a 1989 book by [[Slovenia]]n [[philosopher]] and [[cultural]] [[theorist]] [[Slavoj Žižek]]. The work is widely considered his masterpiece.<ref name="Encyclopædia Britannica Online">{{cite web|url=http://www.britannica.com/EBchecked/topic/1446643/Slavoj-Zizek/301049/The-Sublime-Object-of-Ideology|title=The Sublime Object of Ideology|last=[[Ian Parker (psychologist)]]|work=[[Encyclopædia Britannica Online]]|publisher=[[Encyclopædia Britannica, Inc.]]|accessdate=25 May 2015}}</ref>
==Summary== Žižek thematizes the [[Kantian]] notion of the [[sublime (philosophy)|sublime]] in order to liken [[ideology]] to the experience of something that is absolutely vast and powerful beyond all perception and objective intelligibility. Žižek provides an analysis of "How did Marx Invent the Symptom?", in which he compares the ways in which the notion of symptom runs through the work of [[Karl Marx]] and [[Sigmund Freud]]. Žižek opposes any simplistic reading of the two thinkers, who are shown to have discovered the "[[wikt:kernel|kernel]]" of meaning concealed within the apparently unconnected "forms" of [[commodity|commodities]] (Marx) and [[dream]]s (Freud). The kernel of a commodity's content is labour and its latent meaning is the dream. Žižek thinks it more important to ask why latent content takes a particular form. Žižek therefore argues that according to both Freud and Marx the dream-work and commodity-form itself require analysis.
==Reception== Žižek believes ''The Sublime Object of Ideology'' to be one of his best books,<ref>{{Citation|last=aussiesta|title=Slavoj Zizek Picks His Best Three Books|date=2016-11-25|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=bqUW2uScLio&feature=youtu.be&t=25s|accessdate=2018-05-27}}</ref> while psychologist [[Ian Parker (psychologist)|Ian Parker]] writes in the ''[[Encyclopædia Britannica]]'' that it is "widely considered his masterpiece".<ref name="Encyclopædia Britannica Online">{{cite web|url=http://www.britannica.com/EBchecked/topic/1446643/Slavoj-Zizek/301049/The-Sublime-Object-of-Ideology|title=The Sublime Object of Ideology|last=[[Ian Parker (psychologist)]]|work=[[Encyclopædia Britannica Online]]|publisher=[[Encyclopædia Britannica, Inc.]]|accessdate=25 May 2015}}</ref> Anthony Elliott writes that the work is "a provocative reconstruction of critical theory from Marx to Althusser, reinterpreted through the frame of Lacanian psychoanalysis".<ref>{{cite book |author=Elliott, Anthony |title=Psychoanalytic Theory: An Introduction |year=2002 |publisher=Palgrave |page=117 |isbn=0-333-91912-2}}</ref>
